<br>
According to Verant, Charm is what Enchanters were INTENDED to be about.  They added Tash, Clarity, and all Animation pets other than 1 and 8 at the end of beta.  They told us that we weren't a &quot;pet class&quot; because we should be charming our pets as we go.  Charm is practically the only way we can solo well.  And since when did &quot;Enchanter&quot; (i.e., person who enchants) become equated to mana regeneration and resistance debuffing?  We are intended to charm.<br>
Dire Charm is a perfect fit for our class, and the level cap keeps it from completely overshadowing our higher Charm spells.  As people have said earlier, the &quot;charm a good pet and use it&quot; thing has been around MUCH longer than DC.<br>
<br>
It's ridiculous to give the chanter credit for that extra 66% melee damage.  After all, since a Shaman can slow by 75%, do we credit him with doing three times as much healing as everyone else combined?  Having the Enchanter there DOES improve the group, but unlike adding another damage dealer it can't be done in a vacuum.  An Enchanter is only an effective buffer when he has someone to buff, and you don't need more than one in most cases.  Saying that we're the &quot;most powerful class in the game&quot; (which personally I feel goes to Druids; 2nd place DD, DoTs, SoW, heals, several self-only Clarity-type spells that all stack, ports and evacs...) is a bit of a stretch.<br>
<br>
Now, I do think that the Magician pet is badly underpowered, but only because the mobs are badly overpowered, thanks to Velious.  In fact, this mainly seems to be a Velious issue; I know some level 60 mages who solo just fine in CoM and Chardok, it's only the massive HP of the Velious mobs that gives them fits.  Coincidentally, the massive HP and underconning of Velious mobs is also part of why people claim Dire Charm is overpowered.<br>
The problem with giving the Mage pets more is this though: if the pet is good enough to consistently outfight a level 60 tank with a lot of AAs, then what would stop you from using it to solo with no effort and no risk?  How many classes can solo like that?  So, you've got a pet that is good, but requires DD support for most XP-giving encounters.  Enchanters can charm a pet (and hope you don't lose control) that is even better, to make up for our really bad damage spells.  With Dire Charm you're picking a slightly lower pet for a bit more insurance, although we still go LD enough to keep it from being a popular thing, and against dispelling mobs (say, every dragon) it's worse than useless.<br>
<br>
What I'd suggest is tweaking the Mage Epic pet in one way; make it an unusual class.  Paladin or Ranger would be nice.  It would get heal spells (and heal the Mage), an assortment of other buffs (which it'd buff itself and its caster with), that sort of thing.  But don't make it a godly fighter that outperforms the level 60 tanks.<br>
They could also add a maximum time limit to Dire Charm, say 15 minutes, to make it a less &quot;permanent&quot; pet, but honestly I don't think it's needed. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ukarthunk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Karthunk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/19/02 3:13:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22340.topic&index=93>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The masters of melee damage - enchanters.</span><hr size=1> I would like to add another tid bit about the log of melee dmg that was presented. If that was one person logging that info then I would be willing to bet quite a bit that it's wrong. If you are killing an umber class giant in Kael your people are using max melee and your pets also melee very far from the mob. So, what happens is one person recording misses alot of melee information from certain peeps or pets because they are not in range to record them all at once.<br>
<br>
